//! Legacy VTK structured-points (`.vtk`) reader and writer — `itk::VTKImageIO`.
//!
//! A short text header followed by pixel data that is **always big-endian** when
//! the header says `BINARY`, or whitespace-separated decimal text when it says
//! `ASCII`. `VTKImageIO` reads both and writes whichever `m_FileType` says;
//! SimpleITK never flips that switch, so [`write()`] always emits `BINARY`.
//!
//! # The header ITK writes
//!
//! `WriteImageInformation` (itkVTKImageIO.cxx:638-713) emits exactly:
//!
//! ```text
//! # vtk DataFile Version 3.0
//! VTK File Generated by Insight Segmentation and Registration Toolkit (ITK)
//! BINARY
//! DATASET STRUCTURED_POINTS
//! DIMENSIONS 4 3 2
//! SPACING 5.0000000000000000e-01 1.2500000000000000e+00 3.0000000000000000e+00
//! ORIGIN -2.0000000000000000e+00 4.0000000000000000e+00 7.5000000000000000e+00
//! POINT_DATA 24
//! SCALARS scalars float 1
//! LOOKUP_TABLE default
//! ```
//!
//! Note the trailing space on the `DIMENSIONS` / `SPACING` / `ORIGIN` lines
//! (`<< ' ' << '\n'`), and that the `scientific` / `precision(16)` manipulators
//! are set *after* the `BINARY` line, so only the two float triples carry them.
//! They are `printf("%.16e")`, reproduced by [`scientific16`].
//!
//! A 1-D or 2-D image is padded to three `DIMENSIONS` slots with `1`, three
//! `SPACING` slots with `1.0`, and three `ORIGIN` slots with `0.0` — the
//! `numDims > 1` / `numDims > 2` ternaries at `:674-680`. The **reader collapses
//! the padding back**, so unlike GIPL a 2-D VTK image round-trips as 2-D; see
//! "Dimensions" below. The direction matrix is not written at all and reads back
//! as the identity.
//!
//! `WriteImageInformation` rejects an image whose dimension is not 1, 2 or 3
//! (`:647-651`); `Write` then reopens the file and seeks past the header before
//! writing the pixels.
//!
//! # Dimensions
//!
//! ```cpp
//! if (dims[1] <= 1 && dims[2] <= 1) { this->SetNumberOfDimensions(2); }
//! if (dims[2] <= 1) { this->SetNumberOfDimensions(2); } else { this->SetNumberOfDimensions(3); }
//! ```
//!
//! (`:210-221`) The first `if` is dead — the second subsumes it. The rule that
//! survives is simply *2-D iff `dims[2] <= 1`*, so `DIMENSIONS 4 1 3` is a 3-D
//! image one row tall, and `DIMENSIONS 4 3 1` is 2-D. Ledger §2.100.
//!
//! # The attribute line
//!
//! After `DIMENSIONS`, `InternalReadImageInformation` loops over header lines
//! until one of four attribute keywords appears, matching by **substring** in
//! this order (`:236-352`):
//!
//! 1. `spacing` or `aspect_ratio` — three doubles, first `NDims` kept;
//! 2. `origin` — likewise;
//! 3. `vector` — `numComp = 3`, pixel type `VECTOR`, third token is the
//!    component type;
//! 4. `color_scalars` — `numComp` from the third token (default `1`), pixel type
//!    `1 → SCALAR`, `3 → RGB`, `4 → RGBA`, anything else `VECTOR`; component
//!    type `UCHAR` for `BINARY` and `FLOAT` for `ASCII`, never the file's;
//! 5. `scalars` — third token is the component type, optional fourth is
//!    `numComp` (default `1`); pixel type `SCALAR` at one component and `VECTOR`
//!    otherwise; then one look-ahead line, consumed only if it contains
//!    `lookup_table`;
//! 6. `tensors` — `SYMMETRICSECONDRANKTENSOR`, six components.
//!
//! Any other line — `POINT_DATA 24`, comments — falls through every test and is
//! silently skipped. Because the test is a substring test in that order,
//! `SCALARS vector_field float` is parsed as a `VECTORS` line, and
//! `COLOR_SCALARS` is caught before the `scalars` arm it contains. Ledger §2.101.
//!
//! There is no component-count range check anywhere: upstream's only mention of
//! VTK's documented `(1,4)` range is a `// todo this should be asserted or
//! checked earlier!` comment on the `SCALARS` write branch (`:703-706`). Ledger
//! §2.104.
//!
//! A `TENSORS` file is readable by ITK but not by SimpleITK:
//! `GetPixelIDFromImageIO` has no `SYMMETRICSECONDRANKTENSOR` arm and ends in
//! `"Unknown PixelType"` (sitkImageReaderBase.cxx:213-240). This port
//! **implements** the read (ledger §3.37): a `TENSORS` attribute stores the full
//! 9-component 3×3 matrix per pixel on disk, and `VTKImageIO` reads all nine but
//! keeps the six symmetric components at row-major indices `[0,1,2,4,5,8]` — the
//! diagonal and upper triangle `[a,b,c,d,e,f]` of
//!
//! ```text
//! a b c
//! b d e
//! c e f
//! ```
//!
//! (ASCII `ReadTensorBuffer` hit-hit-hit / skip-hit-hit / skip-skip-hit,
//! `itkVTKImageIO.cxx:415-451`; binary `ReadSymmetricTensorBufferAsBinary`
//! row1=3 / seek1 / row2=2 / seek2 / row3=1, `:494-525`). The result loads as a
//! 6-component vector image.
//!
//! # What a SimpleITK image writes as
//!
//! `sitk::Image` never produces `IOPixelEnum::RGB`/`RGBA` — every
//! multi-component image is an `itk::VectorImage` — so the `COLOR_SCALARS` write
//! branch (`:686-691`) is dead through SimpleITK and [`write()`] never emits it.
//! Reading `COLOR_SCALARS` is fully supported. Ledger §2.102.
//!
//! What is left:
//!
//! * a 3-component vector image → `VECTORS vectors <type>`;
//! * everything else → `SCALARS scalars <type> <ncomp>` + `LOOKUP_TABLE default`,
//!   where `<ncomp>` is the buffer stride (`2` for a complex image).
//!
//! Two consequences, both reproduced. A `ComplexFloat32` image writes as
//! `SCALARS scalars float 2` and reads back as `VectorFloat32` — VTK has no
//! complex type, exactly as MetaImage has none. And a **one**-component vector
//! image writes `SCALARS scalars float 1`, whose reader arm is `numComp == 1 →
//! SCALAR`, so `VectorFloat32` with one component reads back as `Float32`.
//! Ledger §2.103.
//!
//! # 64-bit integers
//!
//! `VTKImageIO::GetComponentTypeAsString` overrides `LONGLONG`/`ULONGLONG` to
//! VTK's `vtktypeint64` / `vtktypeuint64` (`:151-163`) and delegates everything
//! else to `ImageIOBase`. Which of the two an `int64_t` image takes is decided
//! by the host: `MapPixelType<long>` is `LONG` and `MapPixelType<long long>` is
//! `LONGLONG` (itkImageIOBase.h:645-647), and `int64_t` is `long` under LP64
//! (Linux) but `long long` on macOS and Windows. So the same image writes
//! `long` on Linux and `vtktypeint64` on macOS. This port pins the LP64 spelling
//! and accepts all four on read. Ledger §4.72.
//!
//! # ASCII data
//!
//! `Read` delegates to `ImageIOBase::ReadBufferAsASCII`, whose `ReadBuffer`
//! declares `PrintType temp;` **outside** the extraction loop
//! (itkImageIOBase.cxx:800-812). The first `is >> temp` that fails sets `temp`
//! to `0` (or, on overflow, to the saturated limit) and latches `failbit`; every
//! later extraction is a no-op that leaves `temp` alone, so **every remaining
//! component receives that same value**. A short ASCII data block therefore
//! zero-fills rather than erroring. Reproduced by [`read`]; ledger §2.107.
//!
//! `PrintType` is `int` for the three 8-bit component types and the type itself
//! otherwise (itkNumericTraits.h:386/492/614), so `SCALARS scalars
//! unsigned_char 1` ASCII data is decimal integers, not characters, and `300`
//! lands as `44`.
//!
//! Where `PrintType` is unsigned, a negative literal does **not** fail:
//! `num_get::_M_extract_int` accumulates into the unsigned representation and
//! bounds the magnitude by `max`, then negates (locale_facets.tcc:472-475,
//! :576-583). `-1` into an `unsigned short` is `65535` with no `failbit`, while
//! `-70000` overflows to `65535` *with* one. Reproduced by `read_ascii_ints`;
//! ledger §2.105.
//!
//! ASCII **writing** is unreachable through SimpleITK, and lossy where it is
//! reachable: `WriteImageInformation`'s `precision(16)` is set on the `ofstream`
//! it opens and destroys, not on the separate one `Write` opens for the pixel
//! data, which keeps the default 6 significant digits. Not implemented here.
//! Ledger §2.106.
//!
//! # Truncated data and unreadable headers
//!
//! `Read` discards `ReadBufferAsBinary`'s `bool` (`:598`), so a truncated binary
//! file leaves the tail of ITK's freshly-allocated buffer uninitialised and
//! `Read` returns success. C++ UB; [`read`] returns [`IoError::TruncatedData`].
//! Ledger §1.54 / §4.69.
//!
//! `CanReadFile` calls `GetNextLine` four times without catching, so a `.vtk`
//! shorter than four lines makes `ImageIOFactory::CreateImageIO` **throw** where
//! it should have reported "no reader for this file"
//! (`:94-97`). [`VtkImageIo::can_read_file`] returns `false`. Ledger §2.108 /
//! §4.71.
//!
//! `sscanf("%*s %u %u %u", dims, ...)` does not check its return value, and
//! neither do the `SPACING` / `ORIGIN` scans (`:209`, `:241`, `:255`). All three
//! destinations are uninitialised locals (`unsigned int dims[3]`,
//! `double spacing[3]`, `double origin[3]`), so a `DIMENSIONS 4` line leaves
//! `dims[1]` and `dims[2]` indeterminate and sizes the image from them, and an
//! under-filled `SPACING 2.0` line stores indeterminate values through
//! `SetSpacing`; upstream's `1.0` / `0.0` defaults survive only when the line is
//! absent or fully filled. This port raises [`IoError::MalformedVtkHeader`] for
//! an under-filled `DIMENSIONS` and, diverging from upstream, keeps the
//! `1.0` / `0.0` defaults for an under-filled `SPACING` / `ORIGIN` rather than
//! reading indeterminate memory. Ledger §1.55 / §4.70.

